{
  "text": "Failure of the intestinal mucosal barrier results in permeation of microbial and dietary antigens across the intestinal wall. The transmural migration of enteric bacteria or bacterial endotoxins to extraintestinal sites has been termed translocation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Bacterial translocation is assessed by quantitative and qualitative culture of samples of blood, mesenteric lymph nodes, liver and spleen or by the detection of radioactivity in extraintestinal tissues following the oral administration of bacteria labelled with 14C or fluorescein isothiocyanate (FITC). Translocation of endotoxin into the portal or systemic circulation can be assessed using the chromogenic Limulus assay or by measurement of plasma radioactivity after administration of labelled [3H]-, [1251]-or ['*C]endotoxin. There is growing evidence from both in vivo [CITATION_3] ) and in vitro [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] studies that transmucosal passage of intestinal organisms occurs transcellularly.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "32029282",
